# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drua
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:drua/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:drua/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:drua/anthropologist] An **anthropologist** is a scientist engaged in the practice of anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists study aspects of humans within past and present societies.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists are trying to understand the "big picture" of what it means to be human for a group of people in the world.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Social anthropology, cultural anthropology and philosophical anthropology study the norms, values, and general behavior of societies.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropology studies how language affects social life, while economic anthropology studies human economic behavior.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Biological (physical), forensic, and medical anthropology study the biology and evolution of humans and their primate relatives, the application of biological anthropology in a legal setting, and the study of diseases and their impacts on humans over time, respectively.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists usually cover a breadth of topics within anthropology in their undergraduate education and then proceed to specialize in topics of their own choice at the graduate level.
[src:drua/anthropologist] In some universities, a qualifying exam serves to test both the breadth and depth of a student's understanding of anthropology; the students who pass are permitted to work on a doctoral dissertation.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists typically hold graduate degrees, either doctorates or master's degrees.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Not holding an advanced degree is rare in the field.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Some anthropologists hold undergraduate degrees in other fields than anthropology and graduate degrees in anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropological field work requires a faithful representation of observations and a strict adherence to social and ethical responsibilities, such as the acquisition of consent, transparency in research and methodologies and the right to anonymity.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Historically, anthropologists primarily worked in academic settings; however, by 2014, U.S. anthropologists and archaeologists were largely employed in research positions (28%), management and consulting (23%) and government positions (27%).
[src:drua/anthropologist] U.S. employment of anthropologists and archaeologists is projected to increase from 7,600 to 7,900 between 2016 and 2026, a growth rate just under half the national median.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists without doctorates tend to work more in other fields than academia, while the majority of those with doctorates are primarily employed in academia.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Many of those without doctorates in academia tend to work exclusively as researchers and do not teach.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Those in research-only positions are often not considered faculty.
[src:drua/anthropologist] The median salary for anthropologists in 2015 was $62,220.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Many anthropologists report an above average level of job satisfaction.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Although closely related and often grouped with archaeology, anthropologists and archaeologists perform differing roles, though archeology is considered a sub-discipline of anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] While both professions focus on the study of human culture from past to present, archaeologists focus specifically on analyzing material remains such as artifacts and architectural remains.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropology encompasses a wider range of professions including the rising fields of forensic anthropology, digital anthropology and cyber anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] The role of an anthropologist differs as well from that of a historian.
[src:drua/anthropologist] While anthropologists focus their studies on humans and human behavior, historians look at events from a broader perspective.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Historians also tend to focus less on culture than anthropologists in their studies.
[src:drua/anthropologist] A far greater percentage of historians are employed in academic settings than anthropologists, who have more diverse places of employment.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists are experiencing a shift in the twenty-first century United States with the rise of forensic anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] In the United States, as opposed to many other countries forensic anthropology falls under the domain of the anthropologist and not the Forensic pathologist.
[src:drua/anthropologist] In this role, forensic anthropologists help in the identification of skeletal remains by deducing biological characteristics such as sex, age, stature and ancestry from the skeleton.
[src:drua/anthropologist] However, forensic anthropologists tend to gravitate more toward working in academic and laboratory settings, while forensic pathologists perform more applied field work.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Forensic anthropologists typically hold academic doctorates, while forensic pathologists are medical doctors.
[src:drua/anthropologist] The field of forensic anthropology is rapidly evolving with increasingly capable technology and more extensive databases.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Forensic anthropology is one of the most specialized and competitive job areas within the field of anthropology and currently has more qualified graduates than positions.
[src:drua/anthropologist] The profession of Anthropology has also received an additional sub-field with the rise of Digital anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] This new branch of the profession has an increased usage of computers as well as interdisciplinary work with medicine, computer visualization, industrial design, biology and journalism.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists in this field primarily study the evolution of human reciprocal relations with the computer-generated world.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Cyber anthropologists also study digital and cyber ethics along with the global implications of increasing connectivity.
[src:drua/anthropologist] With cyber ethical issues such as net neutrality increasingly coming to light, this sub-field is rapidly gaining more recognition.
[src:drua/anthropologist] One rapidly emerging branch of interest for cyber anthropologists is artificial intelligence.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Cyber anthropologists study the co-evolutionary relationship between humans and artificial intelligence.
[src:drua/anthropologist] This includes the examination of computer-generated (CG) environments and how people interact with them through media such as movies, television, and video.
[src:drua/anthropologist] A central method anthropologists use is participant observation and having informal conversations with people.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Anthropologists take part in both observed conversations and participatory conversations.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Observed is where the anthropologist is observing a conversation that is happening without them directly involved.
[src:drua/anthropologist] On the other hand, participatory conversations are where they are actually talking to the participant which can be in the form of an interview.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Cultural anthropology is a sub-field of anthropology specializing in the study of different cultures.
[src:drua/anthropologist] They study both small-scale, traditional communities, such as isolated villages, and large-scale, modern societies, such as large cities.
[src:drua/anthropologist] They look at different behaviors and patterns within a culture.
[src:drua/anthropologist] In order to study these cultures, many anthropologists will live among the culture they are studying.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Cultural anthropologists can work as professors, work for corporations, nonprofit organizations, as well as government agencies.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropology is a sub-field of anthropology that specializes in the study of how random sounds eventually collect into meaningful language.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropologists are the people studying ways in which language can create and sustain beliefs, relationships, and meaning in the world.
[src:drua/anthropologist] In order to become a professional linguistic anthropologist, people obtain their doctorate degrees in anthropology.
[src:drua/anthropologist] During the PhD, students take 3-4 years of coursework, including classes such as phonetics, morphology, and syntax.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Next, they acquire an in depth understanding of the history and society of a specific place in the world.
[src:drua/anthropologist] After finishing their coursework and finishing exams, they move onto their fieldwork.
[src:drua/anthropologist] There are job opportunities both in and out of academia.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Other jobs may include researching social media and information technology practices and policymaking for bilingual language education.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Another option is creating their own new language.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Some notable anthropologists include: Molefi Kete Asante, Ruth Benedict, Franz Boas, Ella Deloria, St.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Clair Drake, John Hope Franklin, James George Frazer, Clifford Geertz, Edward C.
[src:drua/anthropologist] Green, Zora Neale Hurston, Claude Lévi-Strauss, Bronisław Malinowski, Margaret Mead, Elsie Clews Parsons, Pearl Primus, Paul Rabinow, Alfred Radcliffe-Brown, Marshall Sahlins, Nancy Scheper-Hughes (b.
[src:drua/anthropologist] 1944), Hortense Spillers, Edward Burnett Tylor (1832–1917) and Frances Cress Welsing.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:drua/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:drua/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:drua/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:drua/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:drua/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:drua/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:drua/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:drua/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:drua/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:drua/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:drua/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:drua/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:drua/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:drua/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:drua/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:drua/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:drua/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:drua/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:drua/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:drua/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:drua/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:drua/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:drua/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:drua/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:drua/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:drua/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:drua/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:drua/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:drua/drua] Druas were large, up to 30 metres (98 ft) long, and could carry more than 200 people.
[src:drua/drua] Despite being called "canoes", they were not dugouts, but plank-built ships.
[src:drua/drua] No written record exists of the diffusion of the drua design, but most anthropologists assume its origin in Micronesia, and it probably came to Fiji through the islands of Kiribati and Tuvalu.
[src:drua/drua] The only shunting boat type of Polynesian design is the pahi of the Tuamotu archipelago, but it uses equal hulls and does not appear to be related to other proas.
[src:drua/drua] From Fiji, druas spread to Tonga (where they are called *Kalia*) and Samoa (where they are called *'Alia*).
[src:drua/drua] Captain Cook visited Tonga in his second and third voyages, and noticed that druas were rapidly displacing the Polynesian catamaran design.
[src:drua/drua] Tongan chiefs taking part in Fijian wars would bring them back as prizes of war.
[src:drua/drua] Drua construction eventually became a monopoly of Tongan shipbuilders living in the Fijian Lau Islands.
[src:drua/drua] Druas were sacred canoes in the sense that only aristocrats could own one.
[src:drua/drua] Their main role was as war ships, taking part in naval battles and transporting warriors during raids.
[src:drua/drua] They also had a representative role, and were used to collect taxes.
[src:drua/drua] Following Fijian custom, it was an insult to cross her bows, or to sail to her windward, where the mast stay could be easily cut bringing down the sail.
[src:drua/drua] It was also custom to paddle and not to sail in sight of another chief's territory.
[src:drua/drua] Launching a drua required a bloody ritual, including human sacrifices.
[src:drua/drua] With regard to the human sacrifice associated with the launching ceremonies, Wilkes in the 19th century records that when the Vunivalu of Bau Tanoa Visawaqa launched a canoe 10 or more men were slaughtered on the deck in order that it might be washed with human blood.
[src:drua/drua] The speed of druas became a legendary topic for western sailors, who sometimes confused "Fijian canoes" with "flying proas" (the latter being the original Micronesian design).
[src:drua/drua] The low freeboard of the hulls outside the central platform predates the "wave-piercing" bows of modern racing designs.
[src:drua/drua] The one course that could not be sailed, was with the wind directly aft; otherwise her bows would be driven underwater.
[src:drua/drua] Her performance upwind is unclear, with some authors claiming it to be fast and close to the wind, and others describing it as making too much leeway with the wind in the quarter.
[src:drua/drua] The steering oars were massive, and big canoes would carry one at each end because they were too heavy to transport to the other side while shunting.
[src:drua/drua] The steersman (or men) risked being crippled or killed when hitting big waves.
[src:drua/drua] The chief used to stand on the platform's top, being responsible for cutting the sheet to avoid capsizing.
[src:drua/drua] "The disappearance of the double canoe of Fiji coincided with the close of the nineteenth century.
[src:drua/drua] According to some sources, the last Fijian *ndrua* was built in 1943 on the island of Ongea and was intended to carry copra.
[src:drua/drua] Only two original druas appear to have survived, both of them small.
[src:drua/drua] One, named *Sema Makawa*, is in the New Zealand Maritime Museum.
[src:drua/drua] The second one is *Ratu Finau*, at the Fiji Museum in Suva.
[src:drua/drua] A new Drua, the *i Vola Sigavou*, was completed in 2016 and launched at Navua in Serua province on Viti Levu Fiji's main island.
[src:drua/drua] Today, drua are still a symbol of Fiji, and Fiji's telephone booths are decorated with the characteristic mast-tops of drua.
